Got it — you want the array path and the item field to come from config, not be hard-coded.

Here’s a minimal, backward-compatible pattern that fits your current JSON and code:

1) Config change (tiny)

Keep your existing pointer for the array, and add a sibling key with suffix .itemField to say which field in each array item to read.

"extractedFields": {
  "applicationNumber": "/applicationNumber",
  "policyId": "/policyId",

  "agentId": "/agency",                 // array path (as today)
  "agentId.itemField": "agentRegistrationNumber"  // NEW: value inside each array item
}

(If you prefer a JSON Pointer for the item value, you can also set "agentId.itemField": "/agentRegistrationNumber"—the code below supports both.)

2) Code change (drop-in)

Replace your hard-coded "agentRegistrationNumber" usage with this generic logic:

final ObjectMapper M = new ObjectMapper();
ObjectNode extractedFieldsNode = M.createObjectNode();

// 1) copy simple fields; skip collection fields (those with ".itemField")
if (event.extractedFields != null && !event.extractedFields.isEmpty()) {
    for (Map.Entry<String,String> e : event.extractedFields.entrySet()) {
        String name = e.getKey();
        String ptr  = e.getValue();
        if (name.endsWith(".itemField")) continue;     // handled with its base name
        if ("agentId".equals(name)) continue;          // we'll process generically below

        if (isBlank(ptr) || ptr.charAt(0) != '/') continue; // must be a JSON Pointer
        JsonNode v = newDoc.at(ptr);
        if (v == null || v.isMissingNode() || v.isNull()) continue;
        extractedFieldsNode.set(name, v.isValueNode() ? M.valueToTree(v.asText()) : v);
    }
}

// 2) generic collection extractor for any "<name>" that also has "<name>.itemField"
for (Map.Entry<String,String> e : event.extractedFields.entrySet()) {
    String baseName = e.getKey();
    if (baseName.endsWith(".itemField")) continue;     // skip meta keys

    String arrayPtr = e.getValue();                    // e.g., "/agency"
    if (isBlank(arrayPtr) || arrayPtr.charAt(0) != '/') continue;

    String itemFieldKey = baseName + ".itemField";
    String itemPathConf = event.extractedFields.get(itemFieldKey);
    if (itemPathConf == null) continue;                // not a collection config

    // read the array
    JsonNode arr = newDoc.at(arrayPtr);
    if (arr == null || !arr.isArray()) continue;

    // support relative field name ("agentRegistrationNumber")
    // OR a JSON Pointer within each item ("/agentRegistrationNumber")
    boolean itemIsPointer = !isBlank(itemPathConf) && itemPathConf.startsWith("/");

    ArrayNode out = M.createArrayNode();
    Set<String> seen = new HashSet<>();
    for (JsonNode item : arr) {
        String val = itemIsPointer
                ? item.at(itemPathConf).asText(null)
                : item.path(itemPathConf).asText(null);
        if (val == null || val.isBlank()) continue;
        if (!seen.add(val)) continue;                  // de-dupe
        out.add(val);
    }

    extractedFieldsNode.set(baseName, out);            // e.g., "agentId": ["A1","A2",...]
}

// helper
private static boolean isBlank(String s){ return s == null || s.trim().isEmpty(); }

What this gives you
	•	No hard-coding of "agentRegistrationNumber".
	•	You can rename the logical field ("agentId") or change the array path or inner field purely in config.
	•	Works with other collections too: just add <name> and <name>.itemField pairs to extractedFields.

Example result

With the config above, your output will contain:

{
  "applicationNumber": "APP123",
  "policyId": "POL456",
  "agentId": ["PRU001","PRU002"]    // dynamically extracted from /agency[*]/agentRegistrationNumber
}

If later your schema changes to "/agents" and value at "/reg/id", change only config:

"agentId": "/agents",
"agentId.itemField": "/reg/id"

No code change needed.